# Mew vs. Mewtwo: A Comparative Analysis

Few rivalries in the Pokémon franchise carry as much narrative and mechanical weight as that between Mew and Mewtwo. One is an ancient, naturally occurring being shrouded in mystery; the other is a scientifically engineered clone born from that very mystery. Their relationship touches on genetics, ethics, competitive battling, and in-game accessibility, making them a rich case study in how the franchise explores the tension between nature and artificial creation.

## Origins and the Science of Creation

Mewtwo's existence is fundamentally tied to Mew, having been created using Mew's DNA as the genetic source material through genetic engineering ([Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mewtwo)). The precise origin story differs slightly between media. In the core video games, Mr. Fuji discovered the Mythical Pokémon Mew, gathered samples of its DNA, and used the Pokémon Mansion to create Mewtwo as a modified clone intended to be the most powerful Pokémon in existence ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))). In the film continuity, the origin is more specific: a team of scientists used a fossilized Mew eyelash to create Mewtwo as a genetically enhanced clone ([Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mew_(Pokémon))). The film further elaborates that Mewtwo was created by Giovanni, leader of Team Rocket, who recruited scientist Dr. Fuji to build a cloned supersoldier from the Mew eyelash—with Fuji secretly hoping to use the research to clone his deceased daughter, Amber ([Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pokémon:_The_First_Movie)).

The genetic engineering applied to Mew's DNA did more than replicate it—the intentional alterations made Mewtwo an extremely powerful Psychic-type Pokémon whose abilities surpass those of its genetic source ([Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mewtwo)). Physically, this manifests in Mewtwo's bipedal, humanoid feline-like form, which is significantly more human-like than Mew's due to gene-splicing experiments and deliberate genetic alterations ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))).

## Classification: Natural Mystery vs. Artificial Creation

Despite being derived from Mew, the two Pokémon occupy different official classifications. Mew is designated a Mythical Pokémon representing an ancient, naturally occurring creature, while Mewtwo is classified as a Legendary Pokémon and an artificial Pokémon—a man-made clone produced through genetic modification ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mew_(Pokémon))). This distinction is symbolic as much as taxonomic, establishing a clear divide between natural and artificial origins within the franchise's lore ([Sideshow](https://www.sideshow.com/blog/how-was-mewtwo-created-pokemon-series)). Notably, Mewtwo appears before Mew in the Pokédex numbering despite having been created afterward chronologically ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))).

Thematically, Mew represents natural evolutionary origins as an ancient Pokémon whose DNA became the foundation for Mewtwo's creation ([Sideshow](https://www.sideshow.com/blog/how-was-mewtwo-created-pokemon-series)), while Mewtwo symbolizes the consequences of humanity's attempts to control and improve upon nature through genetic manipulation ([Sideshow](https://www.sideshow.com/blog/how-was-mewtwo-created-pokemon-series)). This is reflected in personality as well: Mew is playful and childlike, whereas Mewtwo's personality is cynical, shaped by the artificial circumstances of its birth ([Sideshow](https://www.sideshow.com/blog/how-was-mewtwo-created-pokemon-series)).

## Narrative and Thematic Roles in the Films

The clearest exploration of these dynamics occurs in *Pokémon: The First Movie*, where Mewtwo serves as the main antagonist. Upon gaining consciousness and learning of Giovanni's intentions to control it, Mewtwo undergoes a profound identity crisis, questioning "who it is, what it is, and where it came from," ultimately killing the scientists and Dr. Fuji upon realizing it is being used as a tool ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/M01)). It goes on to declare that human-Pokémon coexistence is horrific, building a cloned Pokémon army intended to destroy those who oppose it and replace both humanity and natural Pokémon ([Pokémon Fandom](https://pokemon.fandom.com/wiki/MS001:_Pokémon:_The_First_Movie)). As an act of rebellion against the human ideals that created it as a weapon, Mewtwo destroys the very facility where it was made ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Artificial_Pokémon)).

Mew enters at the film's climax, battling Mewtwo to settle which is truly stronger, saving Ash Ketchum when he is caught in their crossfire, and ultimately helping resolve the conflict between the real Pokémon and their clones ([Pokémon Fandom](https://pokemon.fandom.com/wiki/Mew_(anime))). Ash's selfless example softens Mewtwo's heart, prompting it to erase everyone's memories and fly away with its cloned companions ([SciFiDimensions](https://scifidimensions.com/what-inspired-the-making-of-pokemon-mewtwo-returns/)). This arc continues in *Pokémon: Mewtwo Returns*, where Mewtwo searches the western region of Johto for a place beyond human reach, eventually settling at Mount Quena to watch over the clones, believing they do not belong in a world into which they were never naturally born ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_Returns)). Throughout these stories, Mewtwo's character explores identity, free will, and the ethics of genetic engineering ([Instagram](https://www.instagram.com/reel/DTMwYr2Dt9p/?hl=en)), embodying themes of "mad science, vengeance, and grief" born from its manufactured existence ([Sideshow](https://www.sideshow.com/blog/how-was-mewtwo-created-pokemon-series)).

## Competitive Battling and Stat Comparisons

In gameplay terms, Mewtwo decisively outclasses Mew in raw power. Mewtwo boasts a base stat total of 680 ([PokémonDB](https://pokemondb.net/pokedex/mewtwo)) against Mew's balanced total of 600 ([PokémonDB](https://pokemondb.net/pokedex/mew)). While Mew's stats are perfectly even at 100 in each of the six categories ([PokémonDB](https://pokemondb.net/pokedex/mew)), Mewtwo's are heavily specialized: HP 106, Attack 110, Defense 90, Special Attack 154, Special Defense 90, and Speed 130 ([PokémonDB](https://pokemondb.net/pokedex/mewtwo)). Its Mega Evolution, Mega Mewtwo X, pushes this further to a total of 780, shifting its typing to Psychic/Fighting and boosting Defense to 100 and Attack to 190 ([PokémonDB](https://pokemondb.net/pokedex/mewtwo)).

This power differential is reflected competitively. Both Pokémon were placed in the Ubers tier in Generation 1, the only two Pokémon originally assigned there ([Smogon](https://www.smogon.com/articles/rby-ubers-intro)), and both remain in the S Rank of Generation 2 Ubers viability rankings, with Mewtwo ranked 2nd and Mew ranked 3rd ([Smogon](https://www.smogon.com/forums/threads/gsc-ubers-viability-rankings.3654941/)). Mewtwo's exceptional movepool—including Ice Beam, Taunt, and Calm Mind—cements its status as a premier offensive threat ([Smogon](https://www.smogon.com/dex/sm/pokemon/mewtwo/)), giving it superior competitive offensive capabilities compared to Mew thanks to its higher stats and specialization ([All Things How](https://allthings.how/how-to-get-mew-in-every-pokemon-game-stats-moves-and-locations/)).

## Accessibility and Rarity in the Games

Despite Mewtwo's greater power, the two differ sharply in how easily players can obtain them. Mew is event-exclusive, having never been available in the wild across nearly every mainline game, historically requiring special Nintendo events or transfer tricks ([All Things How](https://allthings.how/how-to-get-mew-in-every-pokemon-game-stats-moves-and-locations/)), making it one of the rarest Pokémon in the franchise ([All Things How](https://allthings.how/how-to-get-mew-in-every-pokemon-game-stats-moves-and-locations/)). It remains formally unobtainable through normal gameplay outside of glitches ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))), though it carries a high catch rate of 45 for the rare occasions it can be caught ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))). A notable modern exception is the Poké Ball Plus accessory, which contains a pre-caught Mew ([All Things How](https://allthings.how/how-to-get-mew-in-every-pokemon-game-stats-moves-and-locations/)) transferable into *Pokémon: Let's Go, Pikachu!/Eevee!* or *Sword and Shield* ([All Things How](https://allthings.how/how-to-get-mew-in-every-pokemon-game-stats-moves-and-locations/)), representing a shift toward merchandise-based accessibility for a Pokémon once locked behind events ([Pokémon Fandom](https://pokemon.fandom.com/wiki/Poké_Ball_Plus)).

Mewtwo, by contrast, is catchable through traditional in-game methods in specific locations such as Cerulean Cave in *FireRed/LeafGreen* and *HeartGold/SoulSilver* ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))), making it significantly more accessible than Mew despite its legendary status ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))). That said, actually capturing it remains a challenge: Mewtwo has a low catch rate of 3, equivalent to just 1.6% ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))), making it extremely difficult to secure even when it can be encountered ([Bulbapedia](https://bulbapedia.bulbagarden.net/wiki/Mewtwo_(Pokémon))).

## Conclusion

Mew and Mewtwo represent two sides of a single genetic story: one an ancient, elusive original, the other a scientifically engineered attempt to surpass it. Mewtwo's creation from Mew's DNA gave rise to a Pokémon of superior raw power and more accessible in-game presence, but also to a being burdened by existential questions about identity and purpose that Mew, as a naturally occurring and playful creature, never faces. Their classifications as Mythical and Legendary formalize this symbolic split between the natural and the artificial, while their competitive stats and film narratives reinforce it—Mewtwo as the tormented, overpowered creation striving to define itself, and Mew as the serene original from which that creation sprang.